@denisehotze Oh I misread. He’s probably found somewhere out of sight to rest for the night. You did so well, if he wasn’t going to make it he probably would’ve passed already. As long as he can stay out of sight of predators, he’ll be fine 🙂
@denisehotze Good start. He’s found a place to hide and get his bearings. Check back before it starts to get dark and see if he’s still around.
@denisehotze I’m curious, did he go for any of the food? If he did and his wings and feet are in good shape he’s probably ready to be released

@denisehotze He’s 💩 so that’s good. Moving around a bit is good, his eyes look clear, do his feet look in good shape? I’d maybe take him in the box back to where you found him and see if he’ll try fly.

@denisehotze @HollyStallcup No, better to not. They can aspirate the water and food can get in and irritate the wound. If he’s still struggling for more than 6 hours I think he’s likely to not thrive, but you could try then to add a small bowl of water and see if he goes for it

@denisehotze @HollyStallcup Put him in a box with paper towel at the bottom with a lid and bring him inside somewhere warm but quiet—most often injured birds die of shock if left outside more than their injuries. He can be released when he starts scratching around. That is, ifyou can’t find a rescue for it

Sometimes the cost for an ND person to do simple things is high. Love them by seeing the energy it takes to perform this way is greater than the love you’d feel in return. loving your Nd partner means finding other ways for them to be able to meet your need. Open communication.

If you tell your partner what you need and don’t get it, after they’ve agreed to try, ask why. Maybe they’re adhd & need to build a habit. Maybe executive dysfunction/overstimulation in the store meant they did what they could manage without sapping all their energy for the day

Being loved by an ND person is so much less stressful because effort to communicate and understand/be understood means you evaluate your own and couple needs and expectations together, out loud and have a clear goal to both be loved and be loving with/by each other.

Was it on the grocery list (needs clearly expressed)? Was receiving gifts as part of feeling love (with examples of gifts & expected frequency) too? that’s what this is. ND folk don’t expect their partners to just know how to love them, we tell them & vice versa.

Disagree this is a red flag. People in relationships with neurodivergent folk need to understand how important explicit communication is. We are called rude for stating aloud our needs, then called rude when we can’t read minds of those who don’t state their needs. https://t.co/r6DS6bhLNP

Saw a bear this morning, walked the dog this afternoon, and finally got myself on my partners benefit plan this evening. A good day.

@ServitudeClass I think the more we can give voice to different experiences (which often means labelling them 🤮) the more society can actually see the range in which we all exist, which is how things become normalized. They have to be identifiable to become widely acceptable.

@ServitudeClass It’s very easy for the able bodied or those with hidden disabilities to separate themselves from those with physical or more visible disabilities, and I’d rather offer my experience as an example of the grey area where most of humanity exists, we are more alike than different.

@ServitudeClass Oh I know I’m not subnormal. I struggle both with societal definitions of normal, and lack of dopamine. My worry is if adhd is “normal”, will services and supports become easier to call unnecessary? Does it separate the “in” further from the out, rather than seeing varying shades

@ServitudeClass I agree “normal” is only how society defines who is in/out. Reflecting on adhd, autism, the ND spectrum - adhd can be medically managed, autism is “treated” thru violent social conditioning. some NDs are caused by a biological disability but some are defined by cultural “norm”

@ServitudeClass Adhd is a deficiency of dopamine in the brain. I do experience a lesser ability than those who do not have adhd. Am I less than? No. Is my brain lacking something, yes. If you’re referring to hyperfocus as an ability others do not have, imo its a symptom of dopamine disregulation
RT @pkomo17: Physically disabled person here. Disability Pride is every day. Growing up in a society that tells us disability is a bad word…
TLDR: spend a couple days reading the threads in disability support groups you join before posting and maybe you can avoid being seen as a flagrant ableist jerk in your first post.

Separating yourself from the community means you separate yourself from being part of a community seeking change and instead choosing to remain part of a community who continues to do and promote harm to people like yourself. Self-flagellationnever helped anyone.

You never fit in this society because it thinks if you’re disabled you deserve suffering, if you’re disabled you should be able to “overcome” it, You’re angry because it’s name places you in a group you know has less rights and experiences discrimination, obvs no one wants that

Do your grief work and process the ways you weren’t supported or accommodated, and how this impacted your relationships, school, and work experiences before lashing out at a label without understanding it. It’s not the name that upsets you, but the denial of your own suffering

instead of continuing to disrespect the community you’ve joined online, and separate yourself from the larger community who offers you support, education, and having been fighting for disability rights (your rights) long before you recognized your need for it, read some threads…

If you think deficit, disorder and disability are disrespectful words or have negative connotations that’s you associating two unrelated things. That’s your own ableism and shame showing. I’m sorry you were taught that about others and yourself

So tired of ableism in online adhd groups “it’s not a disorder but a superpower” or “it’s so disrespectful for it to be called a disability when our brains just work differently”. No. Our brains do have a deficit and it does impact my ability to function
